Hey there - I've reviewed your changes - here's some feedback:

**Blocking issues**:
- Discovered a LinkedIn Client secret, potentially compromising LinkedIn application integrations and user data. ([link](https://github.com/21nOrg/tidigit/pull/27/files#diff-4c5e1e5aaf85cedac67b6a48bde35ec45c9abb83894ae5b05697ee59027c3461R887))

**General comments**:

- clipper.utils.ts has grown into a massive file‚Äîconsider splitting it into smaller, platform-specific parser modules (e.g. linkedinParser.ts, instagramParser.ts) to improve maintainability.
- There‚Äôs a lot of duplicated logic for element lookup, URL matching, and date parsing across different social parsers‚Äîextract shared utilities (e.g. generic time and node resolution helpers) to reduce repetition.
- Parser functions assume rigid DOM structures and use console.log directly‚Äîadd try/catch around parsing steps and remove debug logs to ensure failures don‚Äôt break the content script in production.

